=========================================================
CS 4760 Assignment 5 - Resource Management
=========================================================

How to compile:
  make

How to run:
  ./oss -n 5 -s 5 -t 3 -i 0.1 -f oss.log

Options:
  -h            Print help and exit
  -n proc       Total processes to launch (default 18)
  -s simul      Max simultaneous processes (default 18, hard cap 18)
  -t timeLim    Max simulated seconds a child exists (default 5)
  -i fraction   Min fraction-of-second between launches (default 0.5)
  -f logfile    Log file name (default oss.log)

Example:
  ./oss -n 3 -s 2 -t 4 -i 0.6 -f log.txt

=========================================================
Design Decisions
=========================================================

IPC Keys
--------
Both oss and user_proc derive IPC keys using ftok("oss.c", 1)
for shared memory and ftok("oss.c", 2) for the message queue.
Using the source file as the ftok path guarantees unique keys
per user on the shared opsys server, since each user's oss.c
has a different inode number.

Resources
---------
10 resource classes (R0-R9), each with 5 instances, defined
as compile-time constants in shared.h. Resource descriptors
are stored in oss's local memory (not shared memory) since
only oss manages them.

Message Protocol
----------------
oss -> user_proc:  intData == 1  your turn
                   intData == 0  terminate now

user_proc -> oss:  intData > 0   request resource (intData - 1)
                   intData < 0   release resource ((-intData) - 1)
                   intData == 0  terminating

A positive message encodes a resource request as (rIdx + 1)
so that resource R0 can be distinguished from termination (0).
A negative message encodes a release as -(rIdx + 1).

When oss grants a request it sends a reply (intData=1) to the
worker. When oss cannot grant a request the worker is left
blocked in msgrcv - oss does NOT send a reply. When a resource
is released, oss calls the unblock check which scans the process
table for any blocked process waiting for that resource and
sends the deferred reply.

Scheduling
----------
oss uses round-robin scheduling via a lastScheduled index that
rotates through the process table each iteration, ensuring all
unblocked processes get equal turns.

Deadlock Detection
------------------
Banker's detection algorithm runs every simulated second:
  1. Work[r] = available[r]
  2. Finish[i] = false for all occupied PCB slots
  3. Non-blocked processes can always finish
  4. Blocked process i can finish if Work[requestedResource] >= 1
  5. If found: mark Finish[i]=true, add allocation to Work, repeat
  6. Any process still Finish=false is deadlocked

Resolution
----------
When deadlock is detected, oss kills the first deadlocked
process, releases all its resources, unblocks any process
that can now proceed, and re-runs detection until no deadlock
remains.

Termination
-----------
oss stops after opt_n processes launched or 5 real-time
seconds (SIGALRM). Uses sigaction with no SA_RESTART so
msgrcv() is interrupted by the alarm signal. On SIGINT/SIGTERM
oss prints nothing and cleans up all IPC.

Log Output
----------
All output goes to both stdout and the log file. Log writing
stops at 10,000 lines. Every 500ms simulated time the process
table and resource availability are printed. Every 20 granted
requests the full allocation matrix is printed. Every simulated
second deadlock detection runs and results are logged.

=========================================================
Generative AI Use
=========================================================

Generative AI used: Claude (Anthropic, claude.ai)

Prompts (paraphrased):
  1. Explain ftok() and IPC key uniqueness on a shared server
  2. Build Project 5 incrementally starting from Project 3 base
  3. Add command line argument parsing
  4. Add process table and resource table initialization
  5. Add clock advancement and fork one child to test IPC
  6. Add resource request and release logic
  7. Add multiple process support with round-robin scheduling
  8. Fix signal handling so alarm interrupts msgrcv correctly
  9. Add deadlock detection using Banker's algorithm
  10. Add deadlock resolution by killing one process at a time

Summary: Claude was used throughout the entire project to build
incrementally and verify each step before moving to the next.
Each piece was tested on opsys before proceeding. The approach
of building one feature at a time and testing made it easy to
catch and fix issues early. The most valuable contribution was
explaining the ftok() key uniqueness mechanism and correctly
implementing the sigaction/SA_RESTART fix for the alarm signal.